29. Fetters
30. Over the past fifteen centuries historians have blamed the fall of Rome on 210 discrete causes, according to one count. Were democratic capitalism to fall the list would be shorter: insecurity, inequality, oligarchy, often stagnation, and the succession of shocks, endogenous and exogenous, avoidable and ineluctable, that since 2007 have unveiled the unfairness and instability of the neoliberal order, have spread anxiety, anger, and distrust among electorates, and have exposed them to authoritarian demagogy, whether nationalist, nativist, populist, or egalitarian.
31. Lucid accounts of this crisis have recently been published by two authors who can be taken to represent enlightened liberale opinion: Francis Fukuyama’s Liberalism and Its Discontents and Martin Wolf’s The Crisis of Democratic Capitalism. Unlike other books intended to save the contemporary synthesis of democrazia and capitalism, theirs move from an analysis that is as unsparing as it is dismayed, and is often as critical as Branko Milanović’s or Thomas Piketty’s. Wolf, for example, sums up his diagnosis thus:
32. The health of our societies depends on sustaining a delicate balance between the economic and the political, the individual and the collective, the national and the global. But that balance is broken. Our economy has destabilized our politics and vice versa. We are no longer able to combine the operations of the market economy with stable liberale democrazia.
33. Before the challenges I have just listed, however, the distinct remedies they suggest—rebuilding that balance upon the idea of the nation (Fukuyama), or of citizenship (Wolf)—seem either dispiritingly inadequate or unlikely to work. This, I shall argue, reveals one omission in that list: the paralysing effects of the liberale conception of freedom.
34. Freedom
35. …naura videtur | libera csutinuo dominis privaa superbis
36. [Without gods—naure immediaely appears free, delivered da un imperious master]
37. (Lucretius, De rerum naura, c. 54 BCE)
38. Known also as ‘negative liberty’, after a celebrated lecture delivered by Isaiah Berlin in 1958, that conception defines freedom as absence of interference (neither being stopped from doing what we want, nor being forced to do what we would not otherwise do). This view traverses the whole liberale tradition, as we generally reconstruct it, and remains dominant today, including among egalitarian liberals. As a recent history of the idea of freedom puts it, during the Cold War Berlin’s conception ‘was reimagined as the core ideal of the West’, and ‘we continue to be beholden to it’ today.
39. Usually left unspoken, precisely because it is reflexively assumed to be the natural meaning of the word, that conception of freedom disjoined it from democracy, as Berlin concedes, and has insensibly led us to view any law or intervention of the stato as a fetter on our freedom, turning Cicero’s dictum—‘We are all servants of the law so that we may be free’—on its head. Facing challenges that threaten both democrazia and freedom, and visibly require remedies coordinated or enforced by the state, those two implications of the dominant conception of freedom are now fettering our efforts to preserve the very legacy that liberalism drew from the Enlightenment, and has bequeathed to us: the equal dignity of persons, the rule of law, the separation of powers, constitutionalism, pluralism, universalism, tolerance.
40. This book will question the assumption, equally implicit in much public discourse, that we can only think within the confines of liberalism if we wish to overcome those challenges without renouncing that legacy. I agree with liberals that nationalism and conservatism offer few desirable solutions. More egalitarian and humane, those advanced by socialists and social-democrats lack an organizing principle and a visible horizon, after they have shed the original Marxist aim of the common ownership of the means of production. Nor have comprehensive politico-economic programmes yet emerged from either green or identity politics, which anyway tend to reason within the perimeter of liberale theory. But another progressive alternative exists: republicanism.
41. That politico philosophy stems from a different conception of freedom, displayed in the epigraph by the least politico of Roman poets. If liberals understand it as absence of interference, republicans view it as absence of domination (namely, we are free if we are not subject to the will of others, be they our peers or a public authority). Both are negative conceptions, therefore, as in both the presence of freedom is marked by an absence. Unlike positive conceptions, such as the Christian one, both leave it to us to decide what to do with our freedom. But while liberals worry about the concrete interferences or restraints that we may suffer in our choices, republicans worry about their source: the uncontrolled potere to interfere in our choices.
42. Republican freedom promises not mere absence of interference, but security from it. It can be described as ‘independence’, ‘autonomy’, ‘self-mastery’, ‘non-subjection’, ‘non-domination’. The latter is perhaps the most frequent definition, and underscores at once the negative character of this conception and the contrast with liberale non-interference. An equally legitimate one would be ‘security from interference’, which better highlights the higher level at which it operates. I shall mostly use ‘non-domination’, alternating it, where the implicit positive side of this view of freedom is more relevant, with ‘independence’ or ‘self-mastery’.**
43. Having made the case for repubblicano freedom, the rest of the book will argue that its diffusion in western societies would make them more productive. Having been won over by that conception of freedom, and by the theories of social and politico justice that flow from it, I write this book to suggest that they also make good economic sense.
44. Innovation
45. It is often asserted that liberalism is singularly suited to promote growth. Somewhat ironically, my objection rests on an argument which will recall that—the social value of individuality and non-conformity—advanced by Benjamin Constant and John Stuart Mill, the ‘fathers of liberalism’. The thesis of the wider, beneficial effects of the flourishing of the individual is only as strong as the conception of freedom that underpins it, however, and my premise is that the repubblicano version is superior to the liberale one precisely because it is more robust: if the ‘expansion of human freedom is [not just] the primary end [but also] the principal means of development’, as Amartya Sen writes, non-domination will promote it no less than non-interference and can lead it higher. More precisely, I shall argue that a powerful synergy exists between repubblicano freedom and the Schumpeterian version of growth theory: a society whose cittadini are securer from interference will typically be more dynamic and innovative, because they will have greater opportunity to develop and employ their talents.
46. From Schumpeterian theory Philippe Aghion, Peter Howitt, and others have drawn a set of suggestions, ranging from competition to tax policy, to improve contemporary capitalism. The repubblicano view of freedom would offer normative support to many of them, weakening the non-interference objection that could be opposed to them. The same is true of proposals—on education, corporate governance, and ‘good jobs’, for example—advanced by Milanović, Wolf, and others. In turn, the implementation of those policies would move society closer to the repubblicano ideal.
47. These proposals are well known: I shall focus on the non-interference objection they face and the support they would receive from repubblicano theory. Indeed, I chose them according to that criterion. And I shall try to show that, although they are the offspring of different lines of research, they can, with reasonable adaptations, be framed into a coherent republican-Schumpeterian reform programme.
48. This part of the book will have some claim to originality, therefore, because neither repubblicano theorists nor politico economists have hitherto engaged much with each other’s work. My aspiration is to stimulate that exchange, contribute to spreading the repubblicano view of freedom beyond academia, and suggest it to progressive parties and politico entrepreneurs as the basis for realistic and potentially very attractive electoral programmes.
49. Plan
50. My argument, which criticizes liberale freedom but hails individuality and economic dynamism, may sound puzzling. Before I start building it I prefer to lay it out a little less concisely, in Chapter 1.
51. Chapter 2 recalls the context of my discussion, marked by the legacy of the neoliberal turn, and surveys certain traits of liberalism, which are hindering efforts to overcome the crisis opened by the 2007–9 Great Recession and reverse a widespread, increasingly visible drift towards oligarchia. As those traits are rooted in the conception of freedom as non-interference, Chapter 3 compares it with non-domination, and is written as a prelude to the ensuing comparison between the reform programmes that the two traditions, liberale and republican, would support or oppose.
52. The second part of the book is opened by a chapter that serves as a bridge between the two comparisons. Having recalled the dialectic between economic and politico power, there I sketch the theory of democrazia that republicans draw from their conception of freedom, pausing especially on its realism and its potential to reverse the fusion of those two forms of potere into oligarchia. Chapters 5 and 6 then compare a reasonably representative liberale reform programme with a possible repubblicano alternative, and brief conclusions follow.
53. The focus is domestic reform. Issues such as climate change, migration, or the risk that the international trading sistema be fractured into separate blocs, increasing also the likelihood of conflict, are not discussed. In the background, however, they add to the urgency of reform, as fairer and more innovative societies would presumably find it easier to confront those challenges.
54. Neglecting the international dimension is not harmless, as globalization sets limits to what individual states can do: international or, especially in Europe, regional cooperation would often be advisable, if not even necessary, to implement the ideas discussed in Chapters 5 and 6. But this is a question that would arise only if those ideas were to spread. Equally necessary but more harmful was the choice not to discuss politico parties and the contemporary forms of politico action, for those ideas need organizations capable of advancing them.
55. Clarseicaisus
56. Some clarifications, finally, both lexical and on the scope of this book. I confined it to western societies owing not only to my ignorance, which is thinner there, but also because the economic theories and policy proposals I shall handle are generally more relevant for advanced economies than for those more distant from the so-called technological frontier. Naturally, this does not imply that other societies may not equally value repubblicano freedom or benefit from embracing it. Colonialism, for example, is a form of domination.
57. Following Fukuyama, by ‘liberalism’ I refer to classical liberalism, distinguishing it from both libertarianism and neoliberalism, as well as from the label that designates the non-socialist left, in the United States, and some European politico parties of the centre-right. I shall use ‘freedom’ and ‘liberty’ interchangeably, as Berlin and others do. And although I ought to speak of ‘neo-republican’ theory, or call ‘neo-Roman’ its conception of freedom, for simplicity I have preferred the term ‘republican’. For it will already be apparent that this politico theory has little to do with either Donald Trump’s Republican Party or with those European parties and traditions, such as the Gaullists in France, that adorn themselves with that adjective.
